# tls.env.example — Environment variables for automated TLS via Traefik ACME
#
# Copy this file to docker/tls.env and fill in your values.
# Reference: docs/tls-setup.md
#
# Usage:
#   docker compose -f docker/docker-compose.yml -f docker/docker-compose.tls.yml \
#     --env-file docker/tls.env up -d
#
# IMPORTANT: Never commit docker/tls.env to version control.
# The .gitignore already excludes *.env files in the docker/ directory.

# ── Required ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Enable automated TLS mode in the Rust proxy config.
# This tells the proxy process that Traefik is terminating TLS on its behalf,
# so the proxy can surface the correct HTTPS URL in discovery endpoints and status.
# Double-underscore separator: PROXY_TLS__ENABLED maps to tls.enabled in ProxyConfig.
PROXY_TLS__ENABLED=true

# ACME registration email address (Let's Encrypt ToS).
# This address receives certificate expiry warnings from Let's Encrypt.
# Double-underscore: this value is consumed by BOTH the Rust proxy config
# (PROXY_TLS__ENABLED, PROXY_TLS__DOMAIN etc) and by Traefik's ACME email flag.
PROXY_TLS__ACME_EMAIL=admin@example.com

# Public hostname for this proxy deployment (bare hostname, no scheme or port).
# Examples: proxy.example.com   (single host)
#           *.example.com        (wildcard — requires ACME DNS-01 challenge, supported here)
# Env: PROXY_TLS__DOMAIN (double underscore — figment nested struct convention)
PROXY_TLS__DOMAIN=proxy.example.com

# ── Cloudflare Authentication — set ONLY ONE of the following auth modes ─────

# Preferred: Scoped API Token (Zone > DNS > Edit for your zone only)
# Create at: https://dash.cloudflare.com/profile/api-tokens
# Required permissions: Zone > DNS > Edit (scope to the specific zone, not all zones)
# This token has limited blast radius if exposed. Use this option.
CF_DNS_API_TOKEN=

# Legacy break-glass: Global API Key (high-privilege — avoid unless API token unavailable)
# Uncomment the lines below ONLY if you cannot use a scoped API token.
# WARNING: CF_API_KEY has account-wide permissions. Treat it like a root credential.
# Do NOT set both CF_DNS_API_TOKEN and CF_API_EMAIL/CF_API_KEY simultaneously.
# CF_API_EMAIL=
# CF_API_KEY=

# ── Optional ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Let's Encrypt CA server. Defaults to the production server.
# For initial testing, use the staging server to avoid production rate limits.
# Production rate limit: 5 duplicate certificate requests per domain per 7-day window.
# ALWAYS test with staging first, then switch to production once confirmed working.
# Staging: certificates are NOT trusted by browsers (use only for testing).
# ACME_CA_SERVER=https://acme-staging-v02.api.letsencrypt.org/directory

# ── Consul ACL Tokens ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Consul ACL is enabled in production (-acl-default-policy=deny).  Three token
# variables are required in total:
#
#   CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN        — Consul management token (acl:write).
#                              Used by consul-init (KV seed + policy/token
#                              provisioning).  Also used by Traefik to read the
#                              traefik/* KV prefix — see note below.
#   BACKUP_CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN — Backup agent token (backup-agent-write policy).
#                              Write access to proxy/backup/* KV prefix only.
#   PROXY_BACKUP_CONSUL_TOKEN— Proxy-server backup token (proxy-server-backup-rw
#                              policy).  Read/write proxy/backup/* KV only.
#
# NOTE on CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN and Traefik:
#   consul-init DOES NOT yet automatically provision the `traefik-read` and
#   `consul-init-write` least-privilege policies.  To avoid giving Traefik the
#   management token, operators SHOULD create these policies manually (or via a
#   future consul-init update) and set CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN to a narrower token:
#
#     consul acl policy create \
#       -name traefik-read \
#       -description "Read access to traefik/* KV prefix for Traefik" \
#       -rules 'key_prefix "traefik/" { policy = "read" }'
#
#     consul acl token create -policy-name traefik-read
#     # Set CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN to the SecretID printed above.
#
#   Until that is done, setting CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN to the management token is
#   functionally correct but grants Traefik broader-than-necessary ACL privileges.
#
# Bootstrap procedure (one-time, on first deploy):
#
#   Step 1 — Bootstrap the management token:
#
#     docker compose -f docker/docker-compose.prod.yml exec consul \
#       consul acl bootstrap
#
#     This prints a SecretID (management token).  Save it securely — it cannot
#     be recovered.  Set CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN to this value for Step 2.
#
#   Step 2 — Provision backup policies and tokens via consul-init:
#
#     CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN=<management-token> \
#     docker compose -f docker/docker-compose.prod.yml run --rm consul-init
#
#     consul-init creates the following backup ACL policies (idempotent on re-run):
#       backup-agent-write     — write proxy/backup/* KV prefix (backup agent)
#       proxy-server-backup-rw — read/write proxy/backup/* KV prefix (proxy-server)
#
#     Token SecretIDs are printed to stdout on first creation.  The output lines
#     to look for are:
#
#       ">>> Creating backup-agent-token — copy SecretID to BACKUP_CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN"
#       ">>> Creating proxy-server-backup-token — copy SecretID to PROXY_BACKUP_CONSUL_TOKEN"
#
#     On subsequent runs (idempotent), tokens already present are skipped.
#     To rotate a token: `consul acl token delete -id <AccessorID>` then re-run.
#
#   Step 3 — Set all token values below, save as docker/tls.env, and restart:
#
#     docker compose -f docker/docker-compose.prod.yml up -d
#
# Leave all tokens empty if Consul ACL is not yet bootstrapped or in dev mode.
# The dev compose (docker-compose.yml) uses Consul dev mode (no ACL required).

# Management / init token — must have acl:write.
# Used by consul-init for KV seeding and policy/token provisioning.
# Also used by Traefik for KV reads (see NOTE above about privilege scoping).
CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN=

# Backup agent ACL token — backup-agent-write policy (proxy/backup/* write only).
# Provisioned by consul-init; see Step 2 above.
# Required when running docker-compose.backup.yml.
BACKUP_CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN=

# Proxy-server backup ACL token — proxy-server-backup-rw policy (proxy/backup/* rw).
# Provisioned by consul-init; see Step 2 above.
# Used by proxy-server to trigger backup runs and read backup status from Consul KV.
PROXY_BACKUP_CONSUL_TOKEN=

# ── Forward proxy CA certificate (proxy_ca_data volume) ───────────────────────
#
# Forward proxy CA certificate is persisted in the proxy_ca_data Docker volume.
# Set via PROXY_CA_STORAGE_DIR=/ca in docker/docker-compose.prod.yml.
#
# CA rotation: delete ca-cert.pem and ca-key.pem from the volume, then restart.
#
# CA backup:
#   docker run --rm -v proxy_ca_data:/ca -v $PWD:/backup \
#     busybox tar czf /backup/ca_backup.tar.gz /ca
#
# CA restore:
#   docker volume create proxy_ca_data
#   docker run --rm -v proxy_ca_data:/ca -v $PWD:/backup \
#     busybox tar xzf /backup/ca_backup.tar.gz -C /

# ── Backup ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# These variables are required when running docker-compose.backup.yml.
# Add this overlay with:
#
#   docker compose \
#     -f docker/docker-compose.yml \
#     -f docker/docker-compose.prod.yml \
#     -f docker/docker-compose.backup.yml \
#     --env-file docker/tls.env \
#     up -d
#
# Restic repository URL.
# Examples:
#   AWS S3:         s3:s3.amazonaws.com/mybucket/llm-proxy
#   MinIO (local):  s3:http://minio:9000/mybucket/llm-proxy  (requires BACKUP_ALLOW_HTTP_ENDPOINT=true)
# See: https://restic.readthedocs.io/en/latest/030_preparing_a_new_repo.html#amazon-s3
RESTIC_REPOSITORY=

# Restic repository encryption password.
# This password encrypts all data written to the repository.
# Generate a strong password with: openssl rand -base64 32
# KEEP THIS SAFE — without it, the repository cannot be decrypted.
RESTIC_PASSWORD=

# S3 credentials for the Restic repository backend.
# Required when RESTIC_REPOSITORY uses an S3 (or S3-compatible) backend.
AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=

# Cron expression for automated backup schedule.
# Default: 0 2 * * *  (daily at 02:00 UTC)
# Validated against the standard 5-field cron syntax.
# BACKUP_SCHEDULE=0 2 * * *

# Optional: custom S3-compatible endpoint URL (e.g. MinIO, Ceph, Wasabi).
# Must use https:// in production. Set BACKUP_ALLOW_HTTP_ENDPOINT=true for
# local dev / MinIO with an http:// endpoint.
# RESTIC_S3_ENDPOINT=https://minio.example.com
# BACKUP_ALLOW_HTTP_ENDPOINT=

# PostgreSQL credentials for the pg_dump backup target.
# POSTGRES_PASSWORD must match the password used by the TimescaleDB service.
# POSTGRES_HOST, POSTGRES_DB, POSTGRES_USER default to timescaledb / llm_proxy / proxy
# and normally do not need to be set when running the standard compose stack.
# POSTGRES_HOST=timescaledb
# POSTGRES_DB=llm_proxy
# POSTGRES_USER=proxy
# (POSTGRES_PASSWORD is already required above for the main stack)

# ── ACME certificate storage and Consul scope note ────────────────────────────
#
# Traefik ACME certs: stored in the acme_data Docker volume (file-backed at
# /acme/acme.json). Running `docker compose down -v` destroys this volume.
# Back up before running with -v (see docker-compose.tls.yml header comment).
#
# acme_data backup:
#   docker run --rm -v acme_data:/acme -v $PWD:/backup \
#     busybox tar czf /backup/acme_backup.tar.gz /acme
#
# Consul is used for Traefik dynamic configuration (TLS options) only.
# Traefik v3 OSS does NOT support Consul-backed ACME certificate storage
# (that feature is Traefik Enterprise only). ACME certs remain file-backed
# in the acme_data named volume.
#
# Note: Consul KV data (seeded by consul-init) is recreated automatically on
# every `docker compose up` — losing consul_data volume (e.g. via `down -v`)
# is safe. consul-init will re-seed the TLS options on next startup.
